ta for certain constructors. The agent typically generates metadata before compiling, but I'm wondering if we need to add library metadata for org.h2.Driver. It sounds like the main focus is to improve coverage through tests rather than directly updating metadata.\\n\\nHowever, without the right metadata, new tests may fail, so it's clear we might need to include either library metadata or test metadata to support dynamic access.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing H2 Reflection Needs**\\n\\nI'm exploring the use of reflection for `org.h2.Driver`, especially regarding its constructor and how it can access a no-arg constructor if the class is included in the native image. Currently, the H2 metadata seems lacking, which prompts the idea of adding to the reachability metadata. \\n\\nI might need to edit by hand if the agent run doesn’t work. Understanding the metadata schema will be crucial here. It seems like I could also focus on the dynamic call sites covered by test-specific classes, making sure the necessary reflection configuration is included in build.gradle. Also, creating a custom driver that returns a dynamic proxy may solve some of the issues too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Implementing Connection Handling**\\n\\nI'm considering if I need to implement a connection method for my TestDriver. I wonder if I should use `new org.h2.jdbc.JdbcConnection` instead of relying solely on the `TestDriver.connect`. Maybe I can also utilize `DriverManager.getConnection(\\\"jdbc:h2:mem:...\\\")` since the H2 driver is registered, but not our custom driver.\\n\\nSo, if I return `DriverManager.getConnection(\\\"jdbc:h2:mem:jdbcUtilsDriver;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1\\\")` in the connect method, that might work. But will it call all drivers, including unregistered ones? My TestDriver instance isn’t registered, which complicates things.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test implementation**\\n\\nI'm contemplating whether to make the i